affected infants develop severe recurrent infections in early life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate primary treatment for Severe Combined Immunodeficiency?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haematopoietic stem cell transplantation","Intravenous immunoglobulin therapy alone","Prophylactic antimicrobial therapy","Thymus transplantation","Gene therapy with viral vectors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaematopoietic stem cell transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard curative treatment for SCID. When performed early in life, ideally before 3 months of age, it provides the best chance of survival by establishing a functional immune system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin therapy alone\u003C/strong\u003E provides only passive immunity and is insufficient as primary treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic antimicrobial therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is supportive but not curative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThymus transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely used and not standard therapy for most forms of SCID\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGene therapy with viral vectors\u003C/strong\u003E remains experimental for most forms of SCID\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile awaiting definitive treatment, patients require protective isolation, prophylactic antibiotics, and immunoglobulin replacement therapy. Live vaccines are absolutely contraindicated due to risk of disseminated infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haematopoietic stem cell transplantation is the primary curative treatment for Severe Combined Immunodeficiency.","Live vaccines are absolutely contraindicated in SCID as they can cause fatal infections.","Early diagnosis and treatment of SCID is essential for survival, with transplantation ideally performed before 3 months of age."],"references":["Wadbudhe AM, Meshram RJ, Tidke SC. Severe Combined Immunodeficiency (SCID) and Its New Treatment Modalities. Cureus. 2023 Oct 26;15(10):e47759. doi: 10.7759/cureus.47759. PMID: 38022338; PMCID: PMC10676291.","Kohn DB, Hershfield MS, Puck JM, Aiuti A, Blincoe A, Gaspar HB, Notarangelo LD, Grunebaum E. Consensus approach for the management of severe combined immune deficiency caused by adenosine deaminase deficiency. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2019 Mar;143(3):852-863. doi: 10.1016/j.jaci.2018.08.024. Epub 2018 Sep 5. PMID: 30194989; PMCID: PMC6688493.","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:35:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:36:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7686"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66730"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n